'''Abortion in Liechtenstein''' is illegal in almost all circumstances and is punishable by prison terms for the woman and the physician. An attempt to legalize it in 2011 was defeated by voters. In April and November 2012, the [[Landtag of Liechtenstein|Landtag]] failed to advance proposals to relax abortion laws.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schwangerschaftsabbruch: Status quo unverändert |first= |last= |url=http://www.vaterland.li/index.cfm?ressort=home&source=lv&id=17802 |newspaper=Vaterland |date=26 April 2012 |language=German |trans-title=Abortion: Status quo unaltered |accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Schwangerschaftsabbruch ist noch nicht vom Tisch |first= |last= |url=http://www.vaterland.li/index.cfm?id=20654&source=lv&ressort=liechtenstein |newspaper=Vaterland |date=6 November 2012 |language=German|trans-title=Abortion is not yet on the table |accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref>

Section 96 of the Liechtenstein Penal Code, 1987, provides that abortion is illegal except in cases of serious danger to the woman's life or health that can only be prevented with a termination or when the woman was under the age of 14 at the time of conception and unmarried to the man who impregnated her. Illegal abortions are punishable by prison terms of up to three years for the physician and up to one year for the woman. Section 98 of the Penal Code additionally criminalizes performing or encouraging an abortion without a careful inquiry into its medical necessity as well as any type of promotion of abortion services.<ref name="1987law">{{cite web | title = LIECHTENSTEIN. Penal Code, 24 June 1987. (Liechtensteinisches Landesgesetzblatt, No. 37, 22 October 1988, pp. 1-125.) | date = 22 October 1988 | url = http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/population/abortion/LIECHTENSTEIN.abo.htm | accessdate = 7 July 2013 }}</ref><ref name="un">{{cite book |title=Abortion Policies: A Global Review |url= https://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/abortion/doc/liecht.doc |accessdate=7 July 2013 |year=2002 |publisher=United Nations Population Division |volume=1 |format=DOC |isbn= |page= |pages=}}</ref>

In the [[Liechtenstein abortion referendum, 2005|double referendum on abortion]] on 27 November 2005, 81% of voters rejected a "For Life" proposal to prohibit all abortion, while 80% passed the [[Landtag of Liechtenstein|Landtag]]'s counterproposal, which had been condemned by anti-abortion campaigners.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=li012005 |title=Liechtenstein, 27. November 2005 : "Für das Leben" mit Gegenvorschlag |date=20 June 2010 |website=Search Engine for Direct Democracy |publisher= |language= German |accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Nohlen |first1=Dieter |authorlink1=Dieter Nohlen |last2=Stöver |first2=Philip |title=Elections in Europe: A data handbook |url= |accessdate= |year=2010 |publisher=Nomos |location= |isbn=978-3-8329-5609-7 |page=1177}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Defying Church, Voters Endorse Abortion Law |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/28/world/fg-briefs28.3 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=28 November 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Voters defeat restrictive initiative |first=Harry |last=Rosenbaum |url=http://www.dailynews.com/ci_3257356 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130707082504/http://www.dailynews.com/ci_3257356 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=7 July 2013 |agency=Associated Press |date=28 November 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2013 }}</ref>

A proposal to legalize abortion in the first 12 weeks of pregnancy or when the child would be disabled was defeated by 52.3% of voters in the [[Liechtenstein referendums, 2011|2011 referendum]] held on 18 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=li022011 |title=Liechtenstein, 18. September 2011 : Fristenlösung beim Schwangerschaftsabbruch |date=28 September 2011 |website=Search Engine for Direct Democracy |publisher= |language= German |accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref> [[Alois, Hereditary Prince of Liechtenstein|Prince Alois]] had previously threatened to veto the proposal if it passed.
<ref>{{cite news |title=Liechtenstein: No to Legalized Abortion |first= Wendy |last= Zeldin |url=https://www.loc.gov/lawweb/servlet/lloc_news?disp3_l205402820_text |newspaper=Global Legal Monitor |date= 27 September 2011 |accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Liechtenstein rejects plan to legalize abortion |first= |last= |url=https://news.yahoo.com/liechtenstein-rejects-plan-legalize-abortion-133712436.html |agency=Associated Press |date=18 September 2011 |accessdate=7 July 2013}}</ref>

Women in [[Liechtenstein]] who choose to have an abortions must cross the border to either [[Switzerland]] or [[Austria]] to have the procedure carried out legally.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prince of Liechtenstein threatens to leave after vote on his powers |first=Nick |last=Meo |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/liechtenstein/9366747/Prince-of-Liechtenstein-threatens-to-leave-after-vote-on-his-powers.html |agency=The Telegraph|date=30 June 2012}}</ref> Women must also travel to those countries to obtain advice on their options, as they face the threat of prosecution at home.<ref>{{cite news |title=No to Legalized Abortion for women in Liechtenstein |first=Wendy|last=Zeldin|url= https://www.womenfitness.net/news-flash/women_liechtenstein/ |agency=Women Fitness|date=31 January 2012}}</ref> It is estimated that approximately 50 women a year have abortions, either illegally in Liechtenstein or abroad in either Switzerland or Austria.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liechtenstein votes not to legalise abortion |url= https://www.thelocal.ch/20110919/1207 |agency=The Local|date=19 September 2011}}</ref>

