[[Image:Skilandis2.jpg|thumb|Skilandis]]
'''Skilandis''' or '''Kindziukas''' is a [[Lithuania]]n matured [[sausage]] made of meat, fat, salt, pepper and garlic. The ground meat is traditionally pressed into a pig's stomach or bladder, but today may be contained in other skins. The sausage is dried and [[Smoking (cooking)|cold-smoked]].<ref name="Kudirka">{{cite book | title = The Lithuanians: an ethnic portrait | author = Juozas Kudirka |publisher = Lithuanian Folk Culture Centre |url =https://books.google.com/books?id=kkppAAAAMAAJ&q=Skilandis&dq=Skilandis | year = 1991 | page = 29 | accessdate = 10 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.wedlinydomowe.com/sausage-recipes/kindziuk Wedliny Domowe: ''Kindziuk'']</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Art of Taste > Lithuania > Skilandis|url=http://www.fondazioneslowfood.com/en/ark-of-taste-slow-food/skilandis/|website=Slow Foood Foundation|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref> Skilandis dates back to at least the 16th century - the word ''skilandis'' is referred to in documents from various locations across the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]] as early as in the 16th-18th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lithuanian cuisine|url=http://www.2015expo.lt/en/food/lietuviskas-maistas|website=www.2015expo.lt|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>
The term ''skilandis'' has protected status under European Union law.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2010:010:0001:0002:EN:PDF |title= Commission Regulation (EU) No 29/2010 of 14 January 2010 |date = 14 January 2010|publisher=Official Journal of the European Union | accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref> It is added to the list of [[Protected Designation of Origin|Protected Designations of Origin]] (PDO).
==See also== *[[Haggis]] *[[Chireta]] *[[Saumagen]] * [[List of sausages]] * [[List of smoked foods]] * {{portal-inline|Food}}
